    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">An Approach to Security and Performance in a Distributed Wireless Mesh Network</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Krishnakumar S</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Security and Performance<br />Distributed Wireless Mesh Network</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Aug-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0122</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Wireless Mesh Networks (WMNs) is a promising and a key technology
for next-generation wireless networking, offering wireless broadband service access
at a relatively low cost and also used in many applications. Mesh networks will have
full connectivity to the entire network as long as a node is connected to at least one
other node in a mesh network. Mesh protocols automatically determine the best
route through the network and can dynamically reconfigure the network, if a link
becomes unusable. It eliminates many of the disadvantages by offering low cost,
wireless broadband Internet access both for fixed and mobile users. Security in
Wireless mesh networks makes a significant role during transmission. But, when
security is increased, performance decreases. So, it is necessary to increase
performance when security is increased. An effective multi hop based admission
control in distributed wireless mesh networks is developed. A centralized,
measurement-based admission control scheme is effective in controlling traffic load
in WMNs, while incurring very little communication overheads.
A multistage optimization is enhanced and it is related with routing,
bandwidth utilization and power consumption which are developed using the
operations research techniques such as maximal flow model, transshipment model
and minimax optimizing algorithm. The Path creation algorithm is used to find the
multiple paths from source to destination. A multi-stage optimization model is
developed by combining the multi-path optimization model, optimization model in
capacity utilization, energy optimization model and minimax optimizing algorithm.
The performance is estimated by comparing the data rate values of superimposed
algorithm and minimax optimizing algorithm. The optimal solution obtained from
this model is a minimum energy consuming path from source to destination along
with the maximum data rate over each link.
Generating an optimal key at cryptographic stage increases the security of
data. The proposed one is an economic way of generating optimal number of keys
with maximum utility in a wireless network rather than using a single key for each
member. However the problem lies in generating the key management system which
has a single common key for all the members of a virtual group that are essential for
secure communication and should possess availability and least redundancy. The
single key is proposed as ViP key which is shared in the virtual group of members
with polynomial clustering expression, thereby making it simpler to achieve
efficient data transmission instead of using a separate key for each individual
member of that group. Thus, ViP Key management system enables least amount of
keys involving in a single group and has reduced re-keying and updating process
during inclusion or exclusion of members inside a virtual group among the
neighbors in the network.
Broadcast communication is highly prone to attacks from unauthenticated
users in the wireless medium. Techniques have been proposed to make the
communication more secure. TESLA broadcast protocol is used to ensure source
authentication. Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange is used to share the cryptographic
keys in a secured manner. A PKI is developed based on Timed Efficient Stream
Loss-tolerant Authentication (TESLA) and Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange, assuming
that all network nodes in the network are loosely synchronized in time</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13828">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13828</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
